Boboli Gardens History | The Evolution of a Florentine Icon|https://www.boboligardenstickets.com/history/|Cosimo II and Ferdinando II: They expand southward, introducing the Viottolone avenue and the monumental Ocean statue  ...    - 1631: Giulio Parigi elevates the Amphitheatre with an Egyptian obelisk and a basin from Rome's Baths of Caracalla. - 1583-1593: Buontalenti Grotto emerges with limestone stalactites and vivid reliefs, replacing a nursery. - Early 1550s: Bernardo Buontalenti adds the Grotto of the Madama, a mystical oasis with stone beings and animals. - 1549: Duchess Eleonora of Toledo commissions Niccolò Pericoli (Tribolo) for Boboli Gardens - an Italian masterpiece  ...    The Boboli Gardens were begun in 1549 by Niccolò Pericoli, known as Tribolo, for Duchess Eleonora of Toledo. The gardens were designed to be arranged geometrically with a symmetrical, regular positioning of trees and flowerbeds. The planting of hedges and trees, rare and wild plants, and the construction of the fountains began immediately.  ...    ### The age of the Grand Dukes  #### 17th Century During
